This paper proposes a graphical representation of preferences and describes how the structure of the network can be exploited in several inference tasks. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category, as it deals with automated decision making. Additionally, the paper discusses how to order a set of outcomes according to the preference relation, which is a common task in machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also provides a formal semantics for the model, which suggests that it may belong to the Data Structures (cs.DS) sub-category. Furthermore, the paper discusses constructing the best outcome subject to available evidence, which is a task that falls under the Multi-Agent Systems (cs.MA) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with conditional dependence and independence of preference statements, which suggests that it may belong to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category.
